\f0\fs24 \cf0 Anterior shift of the hips is generally caused by a pattern of hypertonic quadratus lumborum and psoas muscles along with weakness and under activity in the abdominal muscles.  This is due to using the psoas to control flexion of the trunk rather than the abdominals.  This results in a tendency for the motion of the pelvis to track with the legs rather than bind to the trunk producing a hyper-extension at the lumbosacral junction on leg extension rather than extension at the hip joint.  To break this pattern, exercises should be initiated that stretch the quadratus lumborum and psoas muscles while strengthening and increasing the coordination in the abdominal muscles.}